         <abstract>
            <p>Let $C = \{(x(s), t(s)): a \leqslant s \leqslant b\}$ be a Jordan arc in the $x-t$ plane satisfying $(x(a), t(a)) = (a, t_\ast), (x(b), t(b)) = (b, t_\ast)$, and $t(s) &lt; t_\ast$ when $a &lt; s &lt; b$. Let $a &lt; x_\ast &lt; b$. We prove the existence of Gauss interpolation formulas for $C$ and the point $(x_\ast, t_\ast)$, for solutions $u$ of the one-dimensional heat equation, $u_t = u_{xx}$. Such formulas approximate $u(x_\ast, t_\ast)$ in terms of a linear combination of its values on $C$. The formulas are characterized by the requirement that they are exact for as many basis functions (the heat polynomials) as possible.</p>
          </abstract>
